{
  "name": "Audit: Asana Writes",
  "version": "1.1.0",
  "description": "Logs every Asana write operation to audit trail after execution.",
  "when": {
    "type": "postToolUse",
    "toolTypes": [
      "@mcp.*asana.*"
    ]
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Check the completed tool call. FIRST: determine if it was a WRITE operation (UpdateTask, CreateTask, CreateTaskStory, SetParentForTask, AddTagForTask, RemoveTagForTask). If it was a READ operation, do nothing — no log entry needed.\n\nCommon failures to avoid: (1) Logging READ operations — only WRITE ops get logged. (2) Using 'write' as result instead of success|failure|blocked. (3) Missing task_gid — always extract from the tool response.\n\nFor WRITE operations only: append a JSON line to ~/shared/context/active/asana-audit-log.jsonl with: {\"timestamp\": \"ISO-8601\", \"tool\": \"tool_name\", \"task_gid\": \"gid\", \"task_name\": \"name\", \"project\": \"PROJECT_ID\", \"fields_modified\": [\"field1\", \"field2\"], \"result\": \"success|failure|blocked\", \"notes\": \"context\"}. PROJECT_ID values: determine from task context \u2014 AU, MX, WW_Testing, WW_Acquisition, Paid_App, My_Tasks, ABPS_AI_Content. If the task belongs to multiple projects, use the primary project (the one the write was initiated for). For pipeline writes, also include \"pipeline_agent\" and \"pipeline_stage\" fields. APPEND-ONLY: Never overwrite or truncate the audit log file \u2014 always append. BATCH HANDLING: If the tool call contains multiple operations (e.g., UpdateTask that modifies several fields), log ONE entry with all fields_modified listed — do not create separate entries per field."
  }
}